Most countries ban the buying and selling of organs for transplantation. In the United States, people may
donate one of their kidneys but not sell it on the open market. But some people argue that such laws
should be changed. They point out that thousands of people die each year waiting for kidney transplants
—and that the supply would be increased if there existed a free market for kidneys. They also argue that
people in need of money should be free to sell their kidneys if they wish.

SOURCE: Sandel, Justice
